WW+c{e_8S`(rW!Rf)n1T: Given a desired character, checks if the currentIndex refers to the correct character (with correct case).
If not, then it corrects the index.
If the requested character is lowercase, but the index that is found was uppercase, then the correct character is at the next index.
The opposite is true for the reverse case.

BlFE,FqZC9-BdxtBj!];: Before a hit object is deleted, these conditions must be fulfilled:
1. Its head has faded out. 2. Its slider body has faded out. 3. Its follow point to the next object has finished.
If hidden mod is on, then only the first hit object needs to draw an approach circle.

EDw0/7%;/zcCBV[3tLQ}: Notelock is always on in relax mod, but there is no shake.
Notes that are hit out of order will cause the active notes before it to be immediately judged
if those notes are within a specific time range from the note that was hit out of order.
If miss, circle disappears faster and does not expand.
If not a miss, circle will fade out normally.

BlFE,FqZC9-BdxtBj!];: Handles Hidden Approach Circle ghost.
Handles Hidden Head Ghost.
Handles normal Head and Approach Circle ghost.
Precomputation for bezier sliders.
Given a set of control points, this function will return a set of points stored in
sliderPointsX and sliderPointsY which defines the points on the slider in chronological order.
The set of points are of equal distance from each other.
However, the distance between each point in one slider and another may differ slightly.
Identical control points signify a red anchor which ends the current bezier curve and starts a new one.
Since bezier curves do not have a fixed velocity, this function will take many samples from the curve and interpolate them.
The number of steps must be a whole number.
The length of each step can be less than or equal to SLIDER_STEP_LENGTH, but never more.
This implies that SLIDER_STEP_LENGTH is the minimum resolution of the drawn slider.

if those notes are within a specific time range from the note that was hit out of order.
If miss, circle disappears faster and does not expand.

Draws a linear slider.
Draws a curved slider.
This weird calculation for transparency was determined from trial and error.
Curves are drawn from many straight strokes. Scratch treats them as individual strokes.
So, semi-transparent strokes overlap with each other, making the slider appear more opaque than it should be.
The shape of this function is like an upside-down sigmoid function.
Ensures that the last point is always drawn.
Used by slider hit objects. This function returns the x and y position of the slider ball at progress (progress)
Given 3 points on an arc (control points), this function solves for
the center, radius, and angle of the arc as well as whether the arc is clockwise or not.
If the slope of AB and BC are different, then the slider s a curve.
Otherwise, it is a straight line.
In the case where the slopes are opposites (e.g. mAB = 2, mBC = -2)
The slider would be treated as a bezier slider since the angle between AB and BC is less than _SLIDER_MIN_ANGLE.
If the gradient of AB and BC are equal, the slider is linear.
Finds the angle of the 3 control points from the center
and figures out whether the arc is clockwise or not.
Given the center (x,y) of a circle with radius r,
this function will return a point on the circle at angle theta
Basically performs binary search to find the nearest timing point before time (time).
Then, sets some properties (slider speed, hitsound volume, and hitsound set) based on that timing point.
If the last timing is uninherited, slider speed only depends on BPM.
Repeat arrows will 'pulse' with the beat of the song.
If the slider hasn't started, then the arrow is only at the end.
If there are more than 2 repeats left, then both arrows should be drawn.
When there is only 1 repeat left, we find out whether the arrow is at the start or end.
Odd number of repeats. Arrow at the end.
Even number of repeats. Arrow at the start.

BlFE,FqZC9-BdxtBj!];: Nested Hits are slider ticks, repeats, and end.
Type "head" can be head, repeat, or end. Their judging methods are identical, so they don't need to be differentiated.
Type "tick" are slider ticks.
For the first slide, slider tick starts appearing before the correct judgement time.
If the slider reaches a repeat arrow, then this will move to the next slider ticks set.
During gameplay, bezier sliders already have their points pre-loaded.
